sections.english:
“How many roots of contention are there, venerable sir?”
“Upāli, there are ten roots of contention. Which are these ten?
Here, Upāli, monks declare a non-offence to be an offence, and an offence to be a non-offence;
they declare a light offence to be a grave offence, and a grave offence to be a light offence;
they declare a gross offence to be a non-gross offence, and a non-gross offence to be a gross offence;
they declare an offence with remainder to be an offence without remainder, and an offence without remainder to be an offence with remainder;
they declare an offence amenable to rectification to be an offence not amenable to rectification, and an offence not amenable to rectification to be an offence amenable to rectification.
These, Upāli, are the ten roots of contention.”
